A. 36                      B. 42                      C. 47                      D. 56

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Here the total number of persons in the

queue = (*29 + 19 – 1) = 47


Note: 29 is derived by adding Ram's

position from left end of the row (24) and his position with respect to Priya

(5). Hence, the correct answer is option C.

questionContent.body:
What was the day of the week on 28th May, 2006?


A. Thursday     B. Friday          C. Saturday      D. Sunday

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Explanation:


28 May, 2006 = (2005 years + Period from 1.1.2006 to

28.5.2006)


Odd days in 1600 years = 0


Odd days in 400 years = 0


5 years = (4 ordinary years + 1 leap year) = (4 x 1 +

1 x 2) 6 odd days


Jan. Feb. March April May


(31 + 28 + 31 + 30 + 28 ) = 148 days


148 days = (21 weeks + 1 day) 1 odd day.


Total number of odd days = (0 + 0 + 6 + 1) = 7 0 odd

day.


Given day is Sunday.

questionContent.body:
In a school, final selection list of the class 12th students who opted for extracurricular activities was posted in the corridor. In the list Vikas was ranked 18th from the top and 36th from the bottom among those who got selected. 12 students did not opt for any extracurricular activity and 7 were disqualified from it. How many students were there in the class?

A. 61                B. 72                C. 57                D. 88

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Solution:


Total number of students who got selected = (Vikas's rank from the

top + Vikas's rank from the bottom) - 1 = 18 + 36 – 1 = 53 Hence, total number

of students who were in class 12th = 53 + 12 + 7 = 72 Hence, the correct answer

is option B.

During a prize distribution ceremony, Vikram was ninth from the left while Janhvi was eighth from the right in the front row. If Hariom was thirteenth from the left and was exactly in the middle of Vikram and Janhvi in the same row then what was the total number of people in the front row?

A. 18                      B. 19                      C. 21                      D. 24

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Here, we know that Vikram was ninth from

the left while Hariom was thirteenth from the left. So, we can say that there

were 3 persons between Vikram and Hariom. And, we also know that Hariom was

exactly in the middle of Vikram and Janhvi so the number of persons between

Hariom and Janhvi will also be 3.

At this point, using the given information

we can create a following figure:

Now, total number of people in the queue =

(8 + Vikram + 3 + Hariom + 3 + Janhvi + 7) = (8 + 1 + 3 + 1 + 3 + 1 + 7) = 24

Thus, the total number of people in the queue was 24. Hence, the correct answer

is option D.

Jan. Feb. March April

questionContent.body:
If 6th March, 2005 is Monday, what was the day of the week on 6th March, 2004?


A. Sunday            B. Saturday         C. Tuesday          D. Wednesday

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Explanation:


The year 2004 is a leap year. So, it has 2

odd days.


But, Feb 2004 not included because we are

calculating from March 2004 to March 2005. So it has 1 odd day only.


The day on 6th March, 2005 will be 1 day

beyond the day on 6th March, 2004.


Given that, 6th March, 2005 is Monday.


 6th

March, 2004 is Sunday (1 day before to 6th March, 2005).

questionContent.body:
The last day of a century cannot be


A. Monday          B. Wednesday    C. Tuesday          D. Friday

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Explanation:


100 years contain 5

odd days.


Last day of 1st

century is Friday.


200 years contain (5

x 2)  3 odd days.


Last day of 2nd

century is Wednesday.


300 years contain (5

x 3) = 15  1 odd day.


Last day of 3rd

century is Monday.


400 years contain 0

odd day.


Last day of 4th

century is Sunday.


This cycle is

repeated.


Last day of a century

cannot be Tuesday or Thursday or Saturday.

A) Q is father of S                     B) D is brother-in-law of M        C) M is sister of S D) S is mother-in-law of M         E) None of above

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Explanation: M is wife of Q, Q is brother of D, so M is

sister-in-law of D D is daughter of S, so M must be daughter-in-law of S – but

gender of S is not known, and D sister-in-law of M.

N @ B $ M % D indicates what relationship between N and D?

A) D is sister of N                     B) D is nephew of N                 C) D is sister in law of N D) N is wife of D

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
N is brother of B, B

is father of M and M is daughter of D, so L is daughter of B and D, B is father

so D is female, and so sister in law of N.

questionContent.body:
“SPECIAL” is written as “65” in a certain code language what will “CONNECT” be coded as?


A) 70               B) 64                C) 32                D) 78               E)74

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Explanation:


SPECIAL → Sum of the place value of each alphabet in the alphabetical

order


SPECIAL = 19+16+5+3+9+1+12 = 65


So, CONNECT = 3+15+14+14+5+3+20 = 74

Statements:

Some cherries are fruits.

All tomatoes are fruits.

All vegetables are cherries.


Conclusions:

Solution:

Some fruits can be cherries.

Seven persons – Kajal, Bhagat, Mandeep, Kiran, Rinku, Pranav, and Shreya have different height and weight such that the tallest one is not the heaviest one.

Kiran is taller than Kajal but not heavier than Shreya. Bhagat is heavier than Rinku but not as much tall as Mandeep. Pranav is heavier than Bhagat but shorter than Mandeep and Bhagat. Kiran is not taller than Pranav. Shreya is not taller than Kajal and not the shortest. Shreya is not heavier than Rinku. Kajal is not lighter than Mandeep who is heavier than Bhagat.
